<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-911-488  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 911 488.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 27 1989 v6 n47 p4(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New Windows development tool draws on HyperTalk.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pallatto, John.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Echelon Development Corp is developing the Descartes developmentsystem for Windows programming.andP;  The system will be similar toHyperTalk on the Macintosh.andP;  Graphical tools and the Descriptscripting language will be used to build applications relativelyquickly.andP;  Descript uses English commands, making it accessible toend users.andP;  Journal is the package's macro programming feature,and such Windows capabilities as Dynamic Link Libraries andcompiled code fragments will be supported.andP;  The $300 package willbe beta tested in Jan 1989 and shipped in Apr 1989, timed tocoincide with Microsoft's release of Windows 3.0.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Echelon Development Corp. (product development).andO;Product:   Microsoft Windows (Graphical user interface) (computer programs)Descartes (Program development software) (product development).andO;Topic:     Program Development ToolsProgramming InstructionSoftware packages.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By John PallattoandM;Startup Echelon Development Corp. is hoping to guide programmers and endusers through the complexities of Windows programming with a newHyperTalk-like development tool for the graphical environment.andM;The Burlington, Mass., company is creating Descartes, a Windows developmentsystem that, like HyperTalk on the Macintosh, gives developers a scriptinglanguage and graphical tools for building new applications.andP;  A scriptinglanguage provides a quick way for users to develop graphical applicationswithout working with a procedural programming language like C.andM;While other Windows programming tools such as CASE:W from CASEworks Inc.andO;offer a type of scripting language none is patterned after HyperTalk.andM;Developers said that a scripting language could speed up and simplify thedesign of Windows applications.andP;  &quot;For somebody who needs to quickly puttogether a Windows interface to a database manager or something like that,this could be interesting,&quot; said Ken Holladay, an application engineer atApplied Systems Technology Inc., a contract programming firm in FortLauderdale, Fla.andM;Descartes' scripting language, called Descript, lets PC users designgraphical user interfaces and complete Windows applications with simpleEnglish-language commands, said Peter Sills, Echelon's vice president ofmarketing and sales.andP;  As a result, Descript can be used by programmers tocreate corporate applications and by end users to build personal ordepartmental programs, he explained.andM;Descartes, to be priced at approximately $300, is slated to go into beta testin late January, with shipment planned for April, he said.andP;  Echelon hastargeted Descartes' release date to tie it to the delivery of Windows 3.0 --a Microsoft offering that is expected to have improved memory-managementfacilities.andM;&quot;Our goal is to get Descartes running under 640K bytes of RAM, but it'spossible that 1M byte will be the minimum requirement,&quot; Sills said.andP;  Thefinal figure will depend on how much memory Windows 3.0 will consume, hesaid.andM;Descartes will also feature a macro programming facility similar to BorlandInternational Inc.'s Superkey or Alpha Software Inc.'s Keyworks, Sills said.andO;Called Journal, the utility will record and play back keystrokes, cursormovements or mouse clicks, and execute them from a Descript command.andM;The program will also support key Windows capabilities such as Dynamic LinkLibraries and compiled code fragments known as D-Codes, which can be reusedin other applications or called from external sources, he noted.andO;</TEXT></DOC>